<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" ?>

<chapter xml:id="introR">
  <title>Getting started with R-Instat</title>

  <blockquote>
    <p><em>Robots are nice to work with.</em> &#x2014;Roger Zelazny<fn>Source: <em>Dismal Light</em> (1968).</fn></p>
  </blockquote>

  <introduction>
    <p>We provide 3 chapters on R-Instat.  This first one is for everyone who hopes to complete the R-Instat version of the lsr book. When you have finished this chapter, if you remain very “R shy”, then omit or just scan the other two chapters.  We hope many will have found this to be easy, and quick enough that they look forward to what’s next.</p>
  </introduction>

  <section xml:id="sec-rinstat-getting-started">
    <title>Getting started</title>

    <p>If you are practicing, rather than viewing, or reading, or skimming, then we assume you have installed R-Instat.  If you needed help then look back to the R-Instat preface.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><p>Start R-Instat.</p></li>
    </ul>
    <p>The starting screen is shown in Fig. 1.</p>
    <p>We combine our introduction to R and R-Instat with examining data.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><p>Choose the 3rd option, namely Import from Library.</p></li>
    </ul>
    <p>This opens an R-Instat dialog.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><p>Click on the down-arrow in the From Package control, Fig. 1.</p></li>
    </ul>
    <p>This shows a list of many R packages, that each contain examples of data.</p>
    <aside>
      <p>The R statistical system consists of a basic core, plus lots of additional packages.  These packages are written in the R language.  Together they provide amazing facilities to help usersyour statistics and data science.</p>
    </aside>
    <figure xml:id="fig-ch3-rinstat-01">
      <sidebyside widths="48% 48%">
        <image source="images/ch3-rinstat/image1.png">
          <description>R-Instat screenshot</description>
        </image>
        <image source="images/ch3-rinstat/image2.png">
          <description>R-Instat screenshot</description>
        </image>
      </sidebyside>
    </figure>
    <ul>
      <li><p>Go down to the package called gosset, then click on the 2nd example, called cassava.</p></li>
      <li><p>Then press Ok.</p></li>
    </ul>
    <figure xml:id="fig-ch3-rinstat-02">
      <sidebyside widths="48% 48%">
        <image source="images/ch3-rinstat/image3.png">
          <description>R-Instat screenshot</description>
        </image>
        <image source="images/ch3-rinstat/image4.png">
          <description>R-Instat screenshot</description>
        </image>
      </sidebyside>
    </figure>
    <p>You have now seen that getting data is easy, if it is in the library and you know where it is.</p>
    <p>That was easy enough that we suggest you do it again!</p>
    <ul>
      <li><p>Choose the File menu, and the option Close Data Book.</p></li>
      <li><p>R-Instat will check whether you are sure.  Click Yes.</p></li>
    </ul>
    <p>Now you return to the starting screen as before.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><p>This time use the File menu again.  Choose the third option to Open from Library.</p></li>
    </ul>
    <figure xml:id="fig-ch3-rinstat-03">
      <sidebyside widths="48% 48%">
        <image source="images/ch3-rinstat/image5.png">
          <description>R-Instat screenshot</description>
        </image>
        <image source="images/ch3-rinstat/image6.png">
          <description>R-Instat screenshot</description>
        </image>
      </sidebyside>
    </figure>
    <p>You return to the same dialog, Fig. xxx.</p>
    <p>Examine this dialog, before pressing Ok.</p>
    <p>It starts roughly as you left it.  That’s often convenient, as you may need to make a small change and then try again.</p>
    <aside>
      <p>This is the parallel of people using R directly.  They write R commands and scripts.  An R user often returns to their script and changes something, and then tries again.  R-Instat works by writing the R script for you.  So, returning to a dialog, changing something and using it again, is just the same.</p>
    </aside>
    <p>This dialog also has 2 option buttons at the top.  This is a feature of quite a lot of the dialogs, but here we only need the first, which is the default.</p>
    <p>There are 5 buttons at the bottom of the dialog and they are the same on every R-Instat dialog.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><p>Click on the second, called Reset.</p></li>
    </ul>
    <figure xml:id="fig-ch3-rinstat-04">
      <sidebyside widths="48% 48%">
        <image source="images/ch3-rinstat/image7.png">
          <description>R-Instat screenshot</description>
        </image>
        <image source="images/ch3-rinstat/image8.png">
          <description>R-Instat screenshot</description>
        </image>
      </sidebyside>
    </figure>
    <p>Now you really are back to where you started before.  Notice also that the Ok button has become disabled.</p>
    <aside>
      <p>The Ok button is automatically enabled when R-Instat considers the dialog is completed fully enough for its task. If you are an R-fan, you may have noticed, and been encouraged by the last button, which says To Script.  This shows that each dialog produces an R-script, but it usually remains hidden.  So R-shy never need worry about scripts.  But R-fan could later work with these scripts.  We return to this in Chapter xxx.</p>
    </aside>
    <p>Every dialog also has the ordinary Help button.  A few, including this one, have a second button, called R-Help.  Notice that is currently also disabled.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><p>Return, as before, to the gosset package and click on the cassava file.</p></li>
      <li><p>The R-Help button is now enabled, so choose it.</p></li>
    </ul>
    <p>The resulting information, also from the gosset package, is in Fig. xxx.  This opens in a new R-Instat window. The data are from 2 countries and the study is of 13 varieties of cassava.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><p>Close the window, and press Ok to import the data again.</p></li>
    </ul>
    <figure xml:id="fig-ch3-rinstat-05">
      <sidebyside widths="48% 48%">
        <image source="images/ch3-rinstat/image9.png">
          <description>R-Instat screenshot</description>
        </image>
        <image source="images/ch3-rinstat/image10.png">
          <description>R-Instat screenshot</description>
        </image>
      </sidebyside>
    </figure>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-rinstat-becoming-a-data-detective">
    <title>Becoming a data detective</title>

    <p>We combine being a data detective with our continued introduction to R-Instat.</p>
    <p>We see, from the bottom in Fig. xxx that our data frame, or data sheet, has 1000 rows and 27 columns.  The names are at the top and that is where we start.</p>
    <p>In R (and hence R-Instat) every column must have a name.  And, unlike a spreadsheet, these names are in a special row, so the data start in row 1.  We like that.</p>
    <p>There is a C after the name in each column, except for age, which is a number column.  The C shows it is a character-type column.</p>
    <p>Like a spreadsheet, there are right-click menus in R-Instat.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><p>Go anywhere into the second variable and right-click.  Look at the menu.  It has some common options for your data.</p></li>
      <li><p>Choose Convert to Factor.</p></li>
    </ul>
    <p>Now the name is followed by an F instead of a C.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><p>Now go to the top of the next 4 columns.  Mark them all, then right-click again,</p></li>
      <li><p>Choose Convert to Factor again.</p></li>
    </ul>
    <figure xml:id="fig-ch3-rinstat-06">
      <sidebyside widths="48% 48%">
        <image source="images/ch3-rinstat/image11.png">
          <description>R-Instat screenshot</description>
        </image>
        <image source="images/ch3-rinstat/image12.png">
          <description>R-Instat screenshot</description>
        </image>
      </sidebyside>
    </figure>
    <p>Now these 5 columns each have an F after the name.</p>
    <p>And your first action as data detective.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><p>Return to the first factor variable and right-click again.</p></li>
      <li><p>This time choose the Levels/Labels option</p></li>
    </ul>
    <p>This gives the summary on the right.  The results show there were 13 levels and that is what we expected, from the documentation.  But it is also good to see, in the data, because any typing error on data entry would have introduced a new variety.</p>
    <figure xml:id="fig-ch3-rinstat-07">
      <sidebyside widths="48% 48%">
        <image source="images/ch3-rinstat/image13.png">
          <description>R-Instat screenshot</description>
        </image>
        <image source="images/ch3-rinstat/image14.png">
          <description>R-Instat screenshot</description>
        </image>
      </sidebyside>
    </figure>
    <p>This is also just your second R-Instat dialog.</p>
    <p>On the left of the dialog is the data selector.  This shows the data that is available to you.  There are 27 variables in the data frame, but here you just see 5 of them.</p>
    <p>That’s because this dialog only works with factors.</p>
    <p>On the right, you see the factor called option_a has been selected for you, because that variable was active when you used the right-click.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><p>Choose the second variable.  Either do a double-click, or click and press the Add button.</p></li>
      <li><p>Check the results, also 13 levels.  Then repeat with the third and check again.</p></li>
      <li><p>Now use the country factor, see below</p></li>
    </ul>
    <figure xml:id="fig-ch3-rinstat-08">
      <image source="images/ch3-rinstat/image15.png" width="80%">
        <description>R-Instat screenshot</description>
      </image>
    </figure>
    <p>This shows, as expected, just the two countries and adds the information that there were 600 respondents from Nigeria and 400 from Cameroon.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><p>Try also gender</p></li>
    </ul>
    <p>This confirm just 2 levels with 462 male respondents and 538 female.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><p>Click on Close to return to the data</p></li>
    </ul>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-rinstat-more-r-instat-and-detecting-work">
    <title>More R-Instat and detecting work</title>

    <ul>
      <li><p>Mark the two variables after age.  Right-click and choose Convert to Factor again, Fig. xxx</p></li>
    </ul>
    <figure xml:id="fig-ch3-rinstat-09">
      <sidebyside widths="48% 48%">
        <image source="images/ch3-rinstat/image16.png">
          <description>R-Instat screenshot</description>
        </image>
        <image source="images/ch3-rinstat/image17.png">
          <description>R-Instat screenshot</description>
        </image>
      </sidebyside>
    </figure>
    <ul>
      <li><p>This time, use the Describe Menu and the first sub-menu, called One Variable.</p></li>
      <li><p>Use the first dialog, called Visualise Data, Fig. xxx</p></li>
    </ul>
    <p>The visualise dialog opens, Fig. xxx.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><p>The Ok button in this dialog is already enabled.  So just use it.</p></li>
    </ul>
    <figure xml:id="fig-ch3-rinstat-10">
      <sidebyside widths="48% 48%">
        <image source="images/ch3-rinstat/image18.png">
          <description>R-Instat screenshot</description>
        </image>
        <image source="images/ch3-rinstat/image19.png">
          <description>R-Instat screenshot</description>
        </image>
      </sidebyside>
    </figure>
    <p>This is the first dialog to produce results in the Output window, Fig. xxx.</p>
    <p>This also continues our investigation of the data.  From the picture we note:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><p>There is confirmation that the data has 1000 rows, or respondents.</p></li>
      <li><p>The grey areas indicate missing valies.</p></li>
      <li><p>The factor variables are shown in green.  The last one has missing values.  Probably we only measured that variable in the second country, namely Cameroon.</p></li>
      <li><p>There is only one numeric variable, which is the age.  It is integer, so the ages are just given as whole years.</p></li>
      <li><p>The remaining variables are still of character type and some are measured in only one of the two countries.</p></li>
      <li><p>The last two variables have scattered missing values, with more in Cameroon than Nigeria.</p></li>
    </ul>
    <p>Now for yet another dialog</p>
    <ul>
      <li><p>Return to the Describe &gt; One Variable menu.  Choose the second dialog, called Summarise.</p></li>
    </ul>
    <p>Pause a little to study this dialog, Fig. xxx.</p>
    <p>There are 3 buttons at the top.  We stick with the first, called Default.</p>
    <p>There is the data selector on the left.  This shows all the variables that could be summarised.</p>
    <p>There is a multiple receiver on the right, because we can summarise many variables at the same time.</p>
    <p>The Ok (and To Script) at the bottom are currently disabled.  You can’t proceed until you have said which columns to summarise.</p>
    <p>Let’s summarise all the columns.  This is easy to do by using the down-arrow next to Add in the data selector, Fig. xxx.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><p>Use the down arrow and the option to Add All.</p></li>
    </ul>
    <p>This is a simple dialog with just one additional option.  (The previous Visualise dialog, Fig. xxx, had more, though they were not needed then.)</p>
    <p>The default value is 12.  But we have already seen, for example in Fig. xxx, that some factors have more levels.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><p>Use the up-arrow on the Factor Level checkbox control and make it 15.  That should be more than enough.</p></li>
      <li><p>Then use Ok.</p></li>
    </ul>
    <figure xml:id="fig-ch3-rinstat-11">
      <sidebyside widths="48% 48%">
        <image source="images/ch3-rinstat/image20.png">
          <description>R-Instat screenshot</description>
        </image>
        <image source="images/ch3-rinstat/image21.png">
          <description>R-Instat screenshot</description>
        </image>
      </sidebyside>
    </figure>
    <p>The results are shown in Fig. xxx and were a mess.</p>
    <p>There are at least 3 solutions to the mess:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><p>Make the output window wider.</p></li>
      <li><p>If your mouse has a wheel, then make the text smaller.</p></li>
      <li><p>We use a third, as below:</p></li>
    </ul>
    <ul>
      <li><p>Click on the word Maximise, towards at the top left, within the Output window, Fig. xxx.</p></li>
    </ul>
    <figure xml:id="fig-ch3-rinstat-12">
      <image source="images/ch3-rinstat/image22.png" width="80%">
        <description>R-Instat screenshot</description>
      </image>
    </figure>
    <p>This shows quite a lot about the default analysis, as well as about our data.</p>
    <p>There are variables of three different types in the data, namely Numeric (just the age column), factor and character.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><p>Numeric columns are summarised with the mean, median etc.</p></li>
      <li><p>Factor columns are summarised with the frequencies.  Those are the same as we saw earlier, via the right-click menu, e.g. Fig. xxx.</p></li>
      <li><p>Character columns are not really summarised at all.</p></li>
    </ul>
    <p>Next, look at the results in more detail.  And an initial result is that our Factor limit of 15 seems ok for all factors, except one.  The factor called consumptionform has more than 15 levels.</p>
    <p>Note also, this variable name “consumptionform” is not allowed to have any spaces as an R column name.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><p>Close the Maximised window.</p></li>
    </ul>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-rinstat-getting-it-right">
    <title>Getting it right</title>

    <p>It is often useful to return to a dialog, so the output is just right.  We illustrate with Summarise.</p>
    <p>You can use the menu again, to use a dialog repeatedly, but another way uses the toolbar, Fig. xxx.  And this is a good excuse to introduce the toolbar.</p>
    <figure xml:id="fig-ch3-rinstat-13">
      <image source="images/ch3-rinstat/image23.png" width="80%">
        <description>R-Instat screenshot</description>
      </image>
    </figure>
    <ul>
      <li><p>Click on the 4th icon in the toolbar.  (It looks a bit like a dialog.)</p></li>
      <li><p>The dialog is as you left it.  Right-click in the receiver and press Clear, Fig. xxx (or select all the variables and delete them.)</p></li>
      <li><p>Choose just age, to see the results in detail for a numeric variable.</p></li>
      <li><p>Press Ok.</p></li>
    </ul>
    <p>This gives 6 numeric summaries.  Results are really easy to get, in R.  The challenge is to understand and interpret them.  This is discussed in Chapters xxx and yyy.</p>
    <figure xml:id="fig-ch3-rinstat-14">
      <sidebyside widths="48% 48%">
        <image source="images/ch3-rinstat/image24.png">
          <description>R-Instat screenshot</description>
        </image>
        <image source="images/ch3-rinstat/image25.png">
          <description>R-Instat screenshot</description>
        </image>
      </sidebyside>
    </figure>
    <p>Practice again with a better summary of the consumptionform variable.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><p>Use the toolbar to return again to the dialog.</p></li>
      <li><p>Remove the age variable and choose consumptionform.</p></li>
      <li><p>Change the number of factor levels to 25, fig xxx.  Press Ok.</p></li>
    </ul>
    <figure xml:id="fig-ch3-rinstat-15">
      <sidebyside widths="48% 48%">
        <image source="images/ch3-rinstat/image26.png">
          <description>R-Instat screenshot</description>
        </image>
        <image source="images/ch3-rinstat/image27.png">
          <description>R-Instat screenshot</description>
        </image>
      </sidebyside>
    </figure>
    <p>The results, in Fig. xxx show there is tidying work needed on this variable, before it can be analysed properly.  For example we learn:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><p>12 respondents have cassava for breakfast, lunch and dinner.</p></li>
      <li><p>2 have cassava for lunch, dinner and breakfast</p></li>
      <li><p>1 has cassava for breakfast, dinner and lunch</p></li>
    </ul>
    <p>There are also other levels that should be combined.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><p>Return yet again to the dialog.</p></li>
      <li><p>Use the middle, skim button at the top.</p></li>
      <li><p>Add all the variables again, Fig. xxx.  Then press Ok.</p></li>
      <li><p>Then click on the 5th icon in the toolbar (it looks like a spreadsheet).</p></li>
    </ul>
    <p>This closes the data window, Fig. xxx, so the whole screen is for the results.</p>
    <p>This summarise option is much more useful for factor variables.  In particular it shows:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><p>The id variable has 1000 unique values.  So, as we would hope, it is different for each respondent.</p></li>
      <li><p>The last 2 character variables – which should later become factors – each have 100s of levels.  They will need a much more detailed study, before analysis, and that’s going to be a lot of tidying work!</p></li>
    </ul>
    <figure xml:id="fig-ch3-rinstat-16">
      <sidebyside widths="48% 48%">
        <image source="images/ch3-rinstat/image28.png">
          <description>R-Instat screenshot</description>
        </image>
        <image source="images/ch3-rinstat/image29.png">
          <description>R-Instat screenshot</description>
        </image>
      </sidebyside>
    </figure>
    <p>Now we return to the 2-window display.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><p>Either click on the 5th, spreadsheet, icon again, or use the curly arrow.</p></li>
      <li><p>Maybe try just the output window and then the return again, so you understand both ways.</p></li>
    </ul>
    <p>You have now seen options for the Output Window.</p>
    <p>You also have another option for the data window.  This uses another property of the toolbar as shown in Fig. xxx.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><p>Press the down arrow next to the data icon, fig xxx.  Choose the last option, called R data viewer.</p></li>
    </ul>
    <p>This gives you an alternative spreadsheet-type viewer of your data.  One difference, from the R-Instat data view, is only apparent for large datasets.  With the R viewer, all the data is available, if you scroll far enough.  With the R-Instat data view you have to move page-by-page.  Each page is for 1000 rows and 50 columns, so these data all fit nicely on the single page.</p>
    <figure xml:id="fig-ch3-rinstat-17">
      <sidebyside widths="48% 48%">
        <image source="images/ch3-rinstat/image30.png">
          <description>R-Instat screenshot</description>
        </image>
        <image source="images/ch3-rinstat/image31.png">
          <description>R-Instat screenshot</description>
        </image>
      </sidebyside>
    </figure>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-rinstat-graphs-are-available-too">
    <title>Graphs are available too</title>

    <p>We are combining our training in being a data detective, with learning about the use of R-Instat.</p>
    <p>So we continue our initial exploration of the cassava data with the introduction of another dialog.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><p>The Describe &gt; One Variable menu again.  This time the third dialog, called graph.</p></li>
      <li><p>Click the down arrow next to Add, and choose Add All.  Then click Ok.</p></li>
    </ul>
    <figure xml:id="fig-ch3-rinstat-18">
      <sidebyside widths="48% 48%">
        <image source="images/ch3-rinstat/image32.png">
          <description>R-Instat screenshot</description>
        </image>
        <image source="images/ch3-rinstat/image33.png">
          <description>R-Instat screenshot</description>
        </image>
      </sidebyside>
    </figure>
    <p>On the dialog side, this is very similar to the One Variable &gt; Summarise.  Once you have used a few dialogs you should be able to use them all.</p>
    <p>The results are in the output window, Fig xxx.</p>
    <p>You learn that the default graph produces a boxplot for a numeric variable, and a bar chart for both factor and character variables.  That’s quite useful.</p>
    <p>R’s graphics are wonderful and this is an initial hint.</p>
    <p>On the data side, these summaries point to our earlier discoveries, that the analysis of the last 2 variables, and the consumption pattern will need some tidying, before analysis.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><p>Use the toolbar icon (4th in the toolbar) to return to the graph dialog.</p></li>
    </ul>
    <p>This introduces a new feature that is common on dialogs.  Some have sub-dialogs and here this is via  the Options button.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><p>Click on the Graph Options button.</p></li>
      <li><p>In the sub-dialog, change the Numeric default of boxplot to Violin + Boxplot</p></li>
      <li><p>Also change the Categorical to a pie chart.  Then Press Return and Ok.</p></li>
    </ul>
    <figure xml:id="fig-ch3-rinstat-19">
      <sidebyside widths="48% 48%">
        <image source="images/ch3-rinstat/image34.png">
          <description>R-Instat screenshot</description>
        </image>
        <image source="images/ch3-rinstat/image35.png">
          <description>R-Instat screenshot</description>
        </image>
      </sidebyside>
    </figure>
    <p>The results are in Fig. xxx.  We don’t like pie charts, and expect you may also not be enthusiastic about them – especially when there are more than a few categories.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><p>Use the toolbar to return to the graph dialog again.</p></li>
      <li><p>Press the Reset button.</p></li>
      <li><p>Choose just the age variable and press Ok.</p></li>
    </ul>
    <p>This is not an exciting graph, but our aim is mainly to show an additional graphics window.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><p>Press the down arrow next to the graph icon, Fig. xxx.  Choose the option called plotly.</p></li>
    </ul>
    <figure xml:id="fig-ch3-rinstat-20">
      <sidebyside widths="48% 48%">
        <image source="images/ch3-rinstat/image36.png">
          <description>R-Instat screenshot</description>
        </image>
        <image source="images/ch3-rinstat/image37.png">
          <description>R-Instat screenshot</description>
        </image>
      </sidebyside>
    </figure>
    <p>This initially looks just the same, Fig. xxx.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><p>But hover near the graph, then it also includes the summary values Fig. xxx.</p></li>
    </ul>
    <p>This makes it much easier to explain the summaries that make up the boxplot.</p>
    <figure xml:id="fig-ch3-rinstat-21">
      <sidebyside widths="48% 48%">
        <image source="images/ch3-rinstat/image38.png">
          <description>R-Instat screenshot</description>
        </image>
        <image source="images/ch3-rinstat/image39.png">
          <description>R-Instat screenshot</description>
        </image>
      </sidebyside>
    </figure>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-rinstat-example-datasets-in-the-lsr-book">
    <title>Example datasets in the LSR book.</title>

    <p>Lsr uses over 40 different datasets.  They are initially available in 2 different ways in the R-Instat library:</p>
    <p>We assume you are starting again, so without data in R-Instat.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><p>Use Import from Library.</p></li>
      <li><p>Choose the second button, Load from Instat Collection.  Then click Browse, Fig xxx</p></li>
      <li><p>Choose the lsr directory and the file called lsrdata.</p></li>
      <li><p>Then press Ok</p></li>
    </ul>
    <figure xml:id="fig-ch3-rinstat-22">
      <sidebyside widths="48% 48%">
        <image source="images/ch3-rinstat/image40.png">
          <description>R-Instat screenshot</description>
        </image>
        <image source="images/ch3-rinstat/image41.png">
          <description>R-Instat screenshot</description>
        </image>
      </sidebyside>
    </figure>
    <p>This imports all the data files into R-Instat together.</p>
    <p>The first sheet will be different, namely the metadata of the files.</p>
    <p>The first data frame provides the metadata for all the xxx datasets, Fig. xxx.  The subsequent sheets have the data files.</p>
    <p>Each dataset is a sheet, like a sheet in a spreadsheet, such as Excel.  In R-Instat the set of sheets together is a databook.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><p>In the toolbar, use the down-arrow next to the dataframe (5th) icon.</p></li>
      <li><p>Choose the 3rd option, to swap the Data with Dataframe Metadata</p></li>
    </ul>
    <figure xml:id="fig-ch3-rinstat-23">
      <sidebyside widths="48% 48%">
        <image source="images/ch3-rinstat/image42.png">
          <description>R-Instat screenshot</description>
        </image>
        <image source="images/ch3-rinstat/image43.png">
          <description>R-Instat screenshot</description>
        </image>
      </sidebyside>
    </figure>
    <p>This window has a row per dataframe and shows the lsr book will use over 40 different datasets as examples.  Just one has over 1000 rows and 14 is the largest number of columns.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><p>Use the same toolbar drop-down to swap back to the usual data view.</p></li>
    </ul>
    <p>We look quickly at just 3 of the datasets, mainly using the dialogs we learned about earlier.</p>
    <p>The biggest dataframe, called afl is the first with data.  It is used in chapters xxx and zzz.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><p>Go to this sheet and scroll right to the bottom.</p></li>
    </ul>
    <p>You only get to row 1000, not to the end of the data.  Fig. xxx shows you can either click to more to a particular page, or use the arrow keys.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><p>Use the double-arrow (≫) and move to the bottom of the data, Fig. xxx.</p></li>
    </ul>
    <figure xml:id="fig-ch3-rinstat-24">
      <sidebyside widths="48% 48%">
        <image source="images/ch3-rinstat/image44.png">
          <description>R-Instat screenshot</description>
        </image>
        <image source="images/ch3-rinstat/image45.png">
          <description>R-Instat screenshot</description>
        </image>
      </sidebyside>
    </figure>
    <ul>
      <li><p>Use the Describe &gt; One Variable &gt; Visualise Data dialog, Fig xxx.  Press Ok.</p></li>
    </ul>
    <p>The results show there are four factor variables, and almost all the others are numeric.  There is one new type.  This is a logical variable, with just the values TRUE and FALSE.</p>
    <p>The results in Fig. xxx also do not have any grey rows.  So there are no missing values in these data.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><p>Next, move to the data frame called agpp, which will be used in Chapters zzz and qqq, Fig xxx.</p></li>
      <li><p>This has 3 variables and all are factors.  So right-click in the first column and choose Levels/Labels</p></li>
    </ul>
    <figure xml:id="fig-ch3-rinstat-25">
      <sidebyside widths="48% 48%">
        <image source="images/ch3-rinstat/image46.png">
          <description>R-Instat screenshot</description>
        </image>
        <image source="images/ch3-rinstat/image47.png">
          <description>R-Instat screenshot</description>
        </image>
      </sidebyside>
    </figure>
    <p>The result shows 100 levels, and there are just 100 rows of data.  So these are unique values, as we would expect for an id variable.</p>
    <p>The other 2 variables seem to be just yes/no.  So, as a good data detective, you may wish to check that each has only 2 levels.</p>
    <figure xml:id="fig-ch3-rinstat-26">
      <sidebyside widths="48% 48%">
        <image source="images/ch3-rinstat/image48.png">
          <description>R-Instat screenshot</description>
        </image>
        <image source="images/ch3-rinstat/image49.png">
          <description>R-Instat screenshot</description>
        </image>
      </sidebyside>
    </figure>
    <p>The next dataframe is called anscombequartet.  It only has numeric variables.  It is used later in this chapter and in Chapter xxx.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><p>Go to this dataframe and the Describe &gt; One Variable &gt; Graph dialog.</p></li>
      <li><p>Use the down-arrow and Add All.</p></li>
    </ul>
    <p>Before pressing Ok, check the dialog to see if anything is different from when you used it last?  You are now producing facets and this may be new to you.  Last time, the dialog gave a Combined Graph.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><p>Press Ok</p></li>
    </ul>
    <p>We are not explaining facets yet, because it is much easier once you have the results.</p>
    <figure xml:id="fig-ch3-rinstat-27">
      <sidebyside widths="48% 48%">
        <image source="images/ch3-rinstat/image50.png">
          <description>R-Instat screenshot</description>
        </image>
        <image source="images/ch3-rinstat/image51.png">
          <description>R-Instat screenshot</description>
        </image>
      </sidebyside>
    </figure>
    <p>Facets are small multiple graphs, and each of the same type.  The default is also, as here, that they each also have the same scale.  Then you don’t clutter the graphs with a separate y axis label and can easily compare across graphs.</p>
    <p>In Fig. xxx it looks as though the first 3 graphs are the same.  Looking at the data confirms they are identical.</p>
    <p>Finally we export these data to Excel.  Then we explain why!</p>
    <ul>
      <li><p>Use File &gt; Export &gt; Export Dataset, Fig. xxx above.</p></li>
      <li><p>Use the Add down arrow to Add All.  Then look at the different ways you can export, Fig xxx.</p></li>
    </ul>
    <p>This is an excellent feature of R.  You can easily mix work in R with other statistical packages.</p>
    <p>However, we want to export all these data frames into a single sile.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><p>So tick the corresponding checkbox.  Then choose Excel from the much shorter selection, Fig. xxx.</p></li>
      <li><p>Press Browse and choose the file location and name.  Press Save.</p></li>
    </ul>
    <figure xml:id="fig-ch3-rinstat-28">
      <sidebyside widths="48% 48%">
        <image source="images/ch3-rinstat/image52.png">
          <description>R-Instat screenshot</description>
        </image>
        <image source="images/ch3-rinstat/image53.png">
          <description>R-Instat screenshot</description>
        </image>
      </sidebyside>
    </figure>
    <p>This does not yet save the file.  Instead you return to the Export dialog</p>
    <ul>
      <li><p>Click Ok.</p></li>
      <li><p>Now check, by opening the Excel file, Fig. xxx.</p></li>
    </ul>
    <figure xml:id="fig-ch3-rinstat-29">
      <sidebyside widths="48% 48%">
        <image source="images/ch3-rinstat/image54.png">
          <description>R-Instat screenshot</description>
        </image>
        <image source="images/ch3-rinstat/image55.png">
          <description>R-Instat screenshot</description>
        </image>
      </sidebyside>
    </figure>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-rinstat-using-an-lsr-dataset">
    <title>Using an lsr dataset</title>

    <p>In the remainder of this book you use the datasets one-at a time.  This is easy from the lsrdata package.</p>
    <p>If you need to clear data from R-Instat then:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><p>Use File &gt; Close Data Book</p></li>
    </ul>
    <p>Then:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><p>Use File &gt; Import from Library, from the usual front screen.</p></li>
      <li><p>Click on the down arrow and choose the lsrdata package.</p></li>
      <li><p>Select the anscombequartet file Fig. xxx.</p></li>
      <li><p>Press Ok.</p></li>
    </ul>
    <figure xml:id="fig-ch3-rinstat-30">
      <sidebyside widths="48% 48%">
        <image source="images/ch3-rinstat/image56.png">
          <description>R-Instat screenshot</description>
        </image>
        <image source="images/ch3-rinstat/image57.png">
          <description>R-Instat screenshot</description>
        </image>
      </sidebyside>
    </figure>
    <p>The main message, from these data is that you should not only get numerical summaries of your data.  Always include graphs as well.</p>
    <p>And R is great for graphs, so this all fits well.</p>
    <p>There are 4 sets of data here.  For the first 3 sets, we can show the main result with the data as they are provided.</p>
    <p>Note there are various edits needed to this dialog.  It looks awful and also doesn’t keep the Y variables when you return to it.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><p>Use Describe &gt; Graphs &gt; Scatterplot</p></li>
      <li><p>Click on the Single Variable button so it changes to Multiple Variables, Fig. xxx.</p></li>
      <li><p>Add Y1, Y2 and Y3 into the multiple receiver.</p></li>
      <li><p>Click on the X Variable receiver, so it becomes turquoise and Add X1</p></li>
      <li><p>Make the point-size larger, maybe 3.  Then press Ok.</p></li>
    </ul>
    <figure xml:id="fig-ch3-rinstat-31">
      <sidebyside widths="48% 48%">
        <image source="images/ch3-rinstat/image58.png">
          <description>R-Instat screenshot</description>
        </image>
        <image source="images/ch3-rinstat/image59.png">
          <description>R-Instat screenshot</description>
        </image>
      </sidebyside>
    </figure>
    <p>The graph shows the 3 sets of points are very different.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><p>Return to the scatterplot dialog.  Add the line of best fit, with standard error also ticked.</p></li>
      <li><p>Press Ok.</p></li>
    </ul>
    <figure xml:id="fig-ch3-rinstat-32">
      <sidebyside widths="48% 48%">
        <image source="images/ch3-rinstat/image60.png">
          <description>R-Instat screenshot</description>
        </image>
        <image source="images/ch3-rinstat/image61.png">
          <description>R-Instat screenshot</description>
        </image>
      </sidebyside>
    </figure>
    <p>We expected 3 lines, but there is only 1 fitted line.</p>
    <p>That’s because each set, though looking very different, has the same fitted line.</p>
    <p>However, this analysis was limited to the first 3 sets only.  That’s because they all had the same X values, i.e. X1, X2 and X3 are identical.</p>
    <p>In addition the graph isn’t very nice.  It is cluttered.  It would be better to have 3 simple graphs.  And R is very good at producing multiple graphs.</p>
    <p>We therefore “reshaped” the data.  R is also excellent at this too.</p>
    <p>This introduces the Prepare menu, Fig. xxx.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><p>Use Prepare &gt; Data Reshape &gt; Stack (Pivot Longer)</p></li>
    </ul>
    <figure xml:id="fig-ch3-rinstat-33">
      <sidebyside widths="48% 48%">
        <image source="images/ch3-rinstat/image62.png">
          <description>R-Instat screenshot</description>
        </image>
        <image source="images/ch3-rinstat/image63.png">
          <description>R-Instat screenshot</description>
        </image>
      </sidebyside>
    </figure>
    <p>The results show small edits in this dialog could be useful.  The set is not made into a factor, and the row labels look unnecessarily complicated.  I thought tidyverse didn’t bother with them?</p>
    <p>This new dataframe has 44 rows, compared with 11 previously.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><p>Right-click and convert set to factor.  (I hope not necessary if done automatically by the stack dialog.)</p></li>
      <li><p>Use the down arrow by the dialog icon on the toolbar to return to the scatterplot dialog, Fig. xxx.</p></li>
      <li><p>Press Reset.</p></li>
    </ul>
    <figure xml:id="fig-ch3-rinstat-34">
      <sidebyside widths="48% 48%">
        <image source="images/ch3-rinstat/image64.png">
          <description>R-Instat screenshot</description>
        </image>
        <image source="images/ch3-rinstat/image65.png">
          <description>R-Instat screenshot</description>
        </image>
      </sidebyside>
    </figure>
    <ul>
      <li><p>Use Y1 as the single variable.  X1 is the X variable.  Click on Facets and include set.  Press Ok.</p></li>
    </ul>
    <figure xml:id="fig-ch3-rinstat-35">
      <sidebyside widths="48% 48%">
        <image source="images/ch3-rinstat/image66.png">
          <description>R-Instat screenshot</description>
        </image>
        <image source="images/ch3-rinstat/image67.png">
          <description>R-Instat screenshot</description>
        </image>
      </sidebyside>
    </figure>
    <p>It is much clearer to show the 4 sets of data in small separate graphs.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><p>Return to the scatterplot dialog.  Add the line, together with the standard error.  Press Ok</p></li>
    </ul>
    <figure xml:id="fig-ch3-rinstat-36">
      <image source="images/ch3-rinstat/image68.png" width="80%">
        <description>R-Instat screenshot</description>
      </image>
    </figure>
    <p>Perhaps different colours would help?</p>
    <ul>
      <li><p>Return to the dialog.  Add set into the By Variable.</p></li>
      <li><p>Also tick the legend checkbox, because it isn’t needed, Fig. xxx.  Press Ok.</p></li>
    </ul>
    <figure xml:id="fig-ch3-rinstat-37">
      <sidebyside widths="48% 48%">
        <image source="images/ch3-rinstat/image69.png">
          <description>R-Instat screenshot</description>
        </image>
        <image source="images/ch3-rinstat/image70.png">
          <description>R-Instat screenshot</description>
        </image>
      </sidebyside>
    </figure>
    <p>We return to this example in a later chapter.  That’s just in case you would like still more?</p>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-rinstat-reflections">
    <title>Reflections</title>

    <p>Just brief notes for now</p>
    <p>We have used factors a lot in this chapter.  R is great at handling factors (columns with categorical data) and this is important in many analyses.</p>
    <p>R is also great for graphics.</p>
    <p>It is also excellent for organising data.</p>
    <p>Using R should make your statistical life more powerful, and maybe even simpler.  Perhaps even more fun?</p>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-rinstat-places-for-discussions">
    <title>Places for discussions</title>

    <p>Data discussion site: <url href="https://github.com/PreTeXtBooks/lsrdata/issues/1" visual="https://github.com/PreTeXtBooks/lsrdata/issues/1"/></p>
    <p>Chapter discussion site: <url href="https://github.com/PreTeXtBooks/lsrinstat/issues" visual="https://github.com/PreTeXtBooks/lsrinstat/issues"/></p>

  </section>

</chapter>
